Solution: I need to find the percentage of patients with regular heartbeat AND low blood pressure.

Let me define events:
- H = high blood pressure
- N = normal blood pressure
- L = low blood pressure
- I = irregular heartbeat
- R = regular heartbeat

Given information:
- P(H) = 16% = 0.16
- P(L) = 19% = 0.19
- P(I) = 17% = 0.17
- P(H|I) = 35% = 0.35
- P(I|N) = 11% = 0.11

First, I'll find P(N):
Since P(H) + P(N) + P(L) = 1:
P(N) = 1 - 0.16 - 0.19 = 0.65

Next, I'll find P(I ∩ N):
P(I ∩ N) = P(I|N) × P(N) = 0.11 × 0.65 = 0.0715

Now I'll find P(I ∩ H):
P(I ∩ H) = P(H|I) × P(I) = 0.35 × 0.17 = 0.0595

Next, I'll find P(I ∩ L):
Since P(I) = P(I ∩ H) + P(I ∩ N) + P(I ∩ L):
P(I ∩ L) = P(I) - P(I ∩ H) - P(I ∩ N)
P(I ∩ L) = 0.17 - 0.0595 - 0.0715 = 0.039

Now I can find P(R ∩ L):
P(R ∩ L) = P(L) - P(I ∩ L)
P(R ∩ L) = 0.19 - 0.039 = 0.151

Converting to percentage:
0.151 × 100 = 15.1%

