Solution: I need to find the number of red balls in the second urn.

**Setting up the problem:**

First urn: 8 red, 7 blue (total: 15 balls)
Second urn: x red, 9 blue (total: x + 9 balls)

**Probability of same color:**

The probability of getting two balls of the same color is:
P(same color) = P(both red) + P(both blue)

**Calculating probabilities:**

P(both red) = (8/15) × (x/(x+9))

P(both blue) = (7/15) × (9/(x+9))

**Setting up the equation:**

(8/15) × (x/(x+9)) + (7/15) × (9/(x+9)) = 151/300

Combining the fractions on the left:
(8x)/(15(x+9)) + 63/(15(x+9)) = 151/300

(8x + 63)/(15(x+9)) = 151/300

**Solving for x:**

Cross-multiplying:
300(8x + 63) = 151 × 15(x+9)

2400x + 18900 = 2265(x + 9)

2400x + 18900 = 2265x + 20385

2400x - 2265x = 20385 - 18900

135x = 1485

x = 1485/135

x = 11

**Verification:**

P(both red) = (8/15) × (11/20) = 88/300
P(both blue) = (7/15) × (9/20) = 63/300
P(same color) = 88/300 + 63/300 = 151/300 ✓

