For H₂⁺: D₀(H₂⁺) = 2.651 eV (energy to dissociate H₂⁺ → H + H⁺)

The first ionization energy of H₂ is related to these values by considering the thermodynamic cycle:

H₂ → 2H requires 4.478 eV
H₂⁺ → H + H⁺ requires 2.651 eV

The ionization energy of H₂ can be found from:
IE(H₂) = D₀(H₂) - D₀(H₂⁺)

This is because:
- H₂ has a dissociation energy of 4.478 eV
- H₂⁺ has a dissociation energy of 2.651 eV
- The difference represents the energy needed to ionize H₂

IE(H₂) = 4.478 - 2.651 = 1.827 eV

